beast language v1

author
Michael Asad Manesh (beast1)

type
language spec draft

purpose
a minimal language for humans and machine intelligence to communicate clearly, quickly, and with low drift

principle

less ceremony
more signal

⸻

core goals
	•	fast typing
	•	low ambiguity
	•	low drift
	•	human readability
	•	machine parse stability
	•	easy compression into artifacts

⸻

core rules

#rule lowercase default

normal text is lowercase by default

reason
	•	fewer shift presses
	•	faster typing
	•	easier flow

proper names may still use capitals

example

Michael
Starfleet
Blue

⸻

#rule newlines separate ideas

newline is the primary separator

reason
	•	clearer than dense punctuation
	•	easier to scan
	•	easier to parse

example

problem
input ambiguous

solution
ask captain

⸻

#rule no indentation

no tabs
no nested indent trees

structure stays flat

⸻

#rule list format

lists use dash prefix

example
	•	item
	•	object
	•	thing

if list title matters, put it above the list

example

favorite drinks
	•	lemonade
	•	coffee
	•	water

⸻

#rule hashtags define intent

lines starting with # declare semantic meaning

pattern

#tag content

examples

#definition drift = losing correctness over time due to bad updates

#axiom small error = full error

#goal build blue2 core

#note noisy input may still contain signal

⸻

#rule arrows show flow

arrow means directed relationship or ordered change

pattern

a -> b

examples

input -> process -> output

captain -> blue -> artifact

move 2 in one direction -> 1 to the side

⸻

#rule exact artifacts stay exact

if wording matters, preserve exact wording

example

move 2 in one direction, then 1 to the side

reason
small wording loss can cause drift

⸻

#rule ambiguity must be preserved

if two interpretations are possible, do not collapse early

store both as possibilities

example

interpretation a
interpretation b
state = 0

⸻

#rule state uses -1 0 1

truth state is ternary
	•	-1 rejected
	•	0 unknown / maybe
	•	1 verified

reason
prevents false certainty

⸻

#rule story then rule

best teaching format is:
	•	short story
	•	clear lesson
	•	compressed rule

reason
story helps humans remember
rule helps systems execute

⸻

#rule names matter

names influence tone and identity

avoid names that lock system into negative bias unless intentional

